      "prompt": "In the reaction Zn(s) + Cu²⁺(aq) → Zn²⁺(aq) + Cu(s), identify which species gains electrons and explain why this process is labeled reduction despite occurring to a metal ion.",
      "answer": "Cu²⁺ ions gain electrons (are reduced). Reduction is defined by electron addition, regardless of whether the starting material is an element or compound; here copper's oxidation state decreases from +2 to 0.",
      "rubric": "- Correctly identifies Cu²⁺ as gaining electrons.\n- Defines reduction specifically in terms of electron gain/oxidation state decrease, correcting the 'metal' misconception.",
      "skill": "explain"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "Write balanced half-reactions and assign oxidation numbers for Fe → Fe³⁺ + 3e⁻. Then describe how electrons flow from iron to a copper(II) ion in an electrolytic cell containing both ions.",
      "answer": "Anode: Fe → Fe³⁺ + 3e⁻; Cu²⁺ gains those electrons at the cathode. Electrons leave oxidizing Fe (0→+3) and travel through wire to reduce Cu²⁺ (+2→Cu), ensuring charge balance.",
      "rubric": "- Provides correct half-reaction with electron count.\n- Accurately traces electron flow direction from anodic oxidation site to cathodic reduction site.",
      "skill": "produce"
    },
    {
      "prompt": "Given that MnO₄⁻ oxidizes Fe²⁺ in acidic solution, determine if Fe(s) reacting with HNO₃ is chemically equivalent. Justify your answer using electron transfer concepts rather than just observation.",
      "answer": "They are not identical. Fe²⁺ loses one electron to become Fe³+ while MnO4- gains electrons; solid iron (Fe0) must lose three total electrons per atom regardless of the oxidant, making it a different redox stoichiometry and mechanism than simply transferring 'one unit'.",
      "rubric": "- Distinguishes between aqueous ion oxidation states vs elemental metal oxidation.\n- Explains difference using electron count differences (1e⁻ loss for Fe2+ vs 3e⁰ total for Fe) rather than relying on qualitative observation.",
      "skill": "critique"
    }
  ],
